HW2 Michal Grotkowski¶

Task 1¶

Given the following table we will compute the fairness metrics:

Blue Will use XAI Will not use XAI Total
Enrolled in training 60 5 65
Not enrolled in training 20 15 35
Total 80 20 100

Demographic parity¶

In order to calculate the demographic parity we need to divide the number of people enrolled in the training in the blue group by the number of people enrolled in the training in the red group, that is: $$\dfrac{65}{50} = 1.3$$

Equal opportunity¶

Equal opportunity is defined as ratios of True Positive Rates that is $TP/(TP+FN)$. Given the table above the TPR for Blue subgroup is $\dfrac{60}{60+20} = 0.75$.
For the red group we can use the probabilistic definition of $TPR$ that is: $P(\hat{Y} = enrolled | A = red, Y = \text{will use XAI}) = \dfrac{25}{50} = 0.5$.
The equal opportunity coefficient is then: $0.75/0.5 = 1.5$

Predictive rate parity¶

Predictive rate parity is defined as $TP/(TP+FP)$, in case of the Blue group this equals to $60/(60+5) = \simeq 0.923$. In case of the red group the probabilistic definition: $$P(Y = \text{will use XAI} | A = red, \hat{Y} = enrolled)$$ means that the Positive Predictive Value is equal to $0.5$. Thus the coefficient is equal to $1.846$.

Task 2¶

For this task I have chosen the adult income dataset. The data has been split into training and test data set in an 80:20 ratio. The prodected attribute I will consider is gender, with the disadvantaged group being the female group.
First I have trained a Logistic Regression model and calculated its fairness metrics:

Model Accuracy Statistical Parity Predictive Parity Equal Opportunity
Logistic Regression 0.80 3.66 1.31 0.88

As we can see, the model violates the $4/5, 5/4$ rule in Statistical Parity and Predictive Parity. In particular the statistical parity has a high vue of over $3$, which means that the model is much more likely to assign a high income to males than females.

I have done the same procedure on the next model, this time preprocessing the data by standardizing the features. The comparison of both models can be seen below:

Model Accuracy Statistical Parity Predictive Parity Equal Opportunity
Logistic Regression 0.80 3.66 1.31 0.88
Logistic Regression (features standardized) 0.85 6.45 0.97 1.14

This time the Predictive Parity value is in the desired range, but the Statistical Parity coefficient has an even higher overall with the model being 6 time more likely to assign a high income to a male than a female.

Bias mitigation¶

In order to try to mitigate the bias I have decided to preprocess the data with reweighing. Reweighing in this case is calculated for each (gender, label) pair and assigned to each instance in the training data. This is added as another feature during training. In order to evaluate the model this feature is then zeroed for each instance in the test set. The exact formula used for calculating the weights is presented in the F. Kamiran and T. Calders, “Data Preprocessing Techniques for Classification without Discrimination,” Knowledge and Information Systems, 2012 paper.
Below is the performance of the Logistic Regression model with standardized features before and after bias mitigation:

Model Accuracy Statistical Parity Predictive Parity Equal Opportunity
Logistic Regression (standardized features) 0.85 6.45 0.97 1.14
Logistic Regression (standardized features + reweighing) 0.85 6.09 1.01 1.12

The performance of the model in this case is not affected, while all of the fairness metrics are pushed towards the value of one. In particular, the Statistical Parity coefficient is lower by ~$0.35$. That being said, the relative change in the coefficient is low enough to not make a meaningful difference. Hence we can see that in our case reweighing helps with the bias although to a lesser degree.

In [6]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

def EqualOpportunity(conf_matrix: np.array) -> float:
    tn, fp, fn, tp = conf_matrix.ravel()
    return  tp/(tp + fn)


def PredictiveRate(conf_matrix: np.array) -> float:
    tn, fp, fn, tp = conf_matrix.ravel()
    return tp/(tp + fp)

def StatisticalParity(conf_matrix : np.array) -> float:
    tn, fp, fn, tp = conf_matrix.ravel()
    return tp + fp

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
model = LogisticRegression()
model2 = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), LogisticRegression())


model.fit(X_train, target_train)
model2.fit(X_train, target_train)
acc1, acc2 = (accuracy_score(target_test, model.predict(X_test)), accuracy_score(target_test, model2.predict(X_test)))
print("Model 1 accuracy : %s \n Model 2 accuracy: %s" % (acc1, acc2))

In [24]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

def ComputeFairness(model, groups, targets):
    conf_matrices = [confusion_matrix(t, model.predict(g)) for g,t in zip(groups, targets)]
    return (StatisticalParity(conf_matrices[1]) / StatisticalParity(conf_matrices[0]),
            PredictiveRate(conf_matrices[1]) / PredictiveRate(conf_matrices[0]),
            EqualOpportunity(conf_matrices[1]) / EqualOpportunity(conf_matrices[0]))

print("Fairness coefficients for model 1: \n Statistical Parity: %s \n Predictive Parity: %s \n EqualOpportunity: %s \n" %  ComputeFairness(model, groups, targets))
print("Fairness coefficients for model 2: \n Statistical Parity: %s \n Predictive Parity: %s \n EqualOpportunity: %s \n" %  ComputeFairness(model2, groups, targets))

Fairness coefficients for model 1: 
 Statistical Parity: 3.6555555555555554 
 Predictive Parity: 1.312543839139584 
 EqualOpportunity: 0.8761283607641724 

Fairness coefficients for model 2: 
 Statistical Parity: 6.450592885375494 
 Predictive Parity: 0.9670959057198009 
 EqualOpportunity: 1.139120612431564

from itertools import combinations
weighted_X_train = X_train.copy()
weighted_X_test = X_test.copy()
weighted_X_train["importance"] = np.ones(X_train.shape[0])
weighted_X_test["importance"] = np.zeros(X_test.shape[0])
for a in range(2):
    for b in range(2):
         gender_group = X_train["gender_Male"] == a
         target_group = target_train == b
         weight = np.sum(gender_group) * np.sum(target_group) / (X_train.shape[0] * np.sum(gender_group * target_group))
         weighted_X_train.iloc[np.array(gender_group * target_group), -1] = weight
         print("Gender_male : %s, target value: %s, Calculated weight: %s" % (a, b, weight))


print(weighted_X_train["importance"], weighted_X_test["importance"])
